The issue here is one of style declarations of equal specificity competing with each other. 

Give the `&lt;a&gt;` elements in the `.navbar` a specific class like:

    &lt;a class=&quot;navbarAnchor&quot;&gt;

Then you can explicitly style:

    .navbarAnchor {
      color: rgb(255, 255, 255);
    }

in various contexts without needing to refer to relationships between the anchors and their parent / ancestor elements.

If necessary (and it might well not be), you can reference:

      .navbarAnchor,
      .navbarAnchor:link,
      .navbarAnchor:visited,
      .navbarAnchor:hover,
      .navbarAnchor:active {
      color: rgb(255, 255, 255);
    }

_______

**N.B.** It&#39;s not for everyone and it&#39;s not suitable for every situation but **BEM** methodology (and related methodologies like **ABEM**) is a very good way to tame specificity issues in CSS.

After I first came across **BEM**, I ignored it for years, because it was quite counter to the way I had been working.

I came back to it late last year and appreciated far more than I ever had before how its deliberate focus on class-based rather than relationship-based selectors can hugely simplify the maintenance of stylesheets, by ensuring almost every selector in your stylesheet has the same specificity level.

Here is a good place to start:

https://css-tricks.com/abem-useful-adaptation-bem/

